Note: ============================================================================
Note: Core stat Implementation
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "do_stat" that takes file_path as Integer, stat_buffer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Execute stat syscall with platform-specific handling
    Note: Returns 0 on success, non-zero on failure

    Let platform_id be proc detect_platform
    Let config be proc get_stat_config with platform_id

    If config is equal to 0:
        Note: Unknown platform
        Return minus 1
    End If

    Let syscall_num be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with config, 0

    Note: Runa String values are pointers to NUL-terminated byte sequences,
    Note: so file_path is already a valid C-string for the kernel. No copy
    Note: or conversion is required before passing it to the stat syscall.

    Note: Windows platforms (6, 7) have no POSIX stat; Win32 callers must
    Note: use file_io_open + fstat or the future win32_get_file_info. We
    Note: return -1 here to signal "not supported on this platform", which
    Note: matches POSIX-style syscall error returns.
    If platform_id is equal to 6 or platform_id is equal to 7:
        Return minus 1
    End If

    Note: POSIX stat syscall (all other platforms) routed through the
    Note: platform-correct 2-arg / 4-arg ABI dispatcher.
    Let result be proc do_stat_syscall with platform_id, syscall_num, file_path, stat_buffer

    Note: Normalize syscall return to 0-on-success, -1-on-error. POSIX stat
    Note: returns 0 on success; the Linux kernel writes a negative errno on
    Note: the negative-return path. Callers downstream test for nonzero.
    If result is less than 0:
        Return minus 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "do_stat_syscall" that takes platform_id as Integer, syscall_num as Integer, path as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Dispatch the per-platform stat syscall using the correct kernel ABI
    shape. POSIX-style stat is a 2-argument syscall stat(path, statbuf)
    on most platforms, but Linux ARM64 and RISC-V kernels dropped 2-arg
    stat entirely in favor of the 4-argument fstatat(dirfd, path, statbuf,
    flags) variant. Linux ARM32 still exposes 2-arg stat64 (syscall 106)
    for legacy compat, so it stays on the 2-arg path.

    Platform routing:
        platform_id  syscall    arg shape       AT_FDCWD/flags
        ===========  =========  ==============  ==============
         1 LinuxX64    stat    2-arg            n/a
         2 LinuxARM64  fstatat 4-arg            -100, 0
         3 LinuxARM32  stat64  2-arg            n/a (legacy)
         4 DarwinX64   stat64  2-arg            n/a
         5 DarwinARM64 stat64  2-arg            n/a
         8 FreeBSDX64  stat    2-arg            n/a
         9 FreeBSDARM  stat    2-arg            n/a
        10 NetBSDX64   __stat50 2-arg           n/a
        11 NetBSDARM   __stat50 2-arg           n/a
        12 OpenBSDX64  stat    2-arg            n/a
        13 OpenBSDARM  stat    2-arg            n/a
        14 RISC-V 32   fstatat 4-arg            -100, 0
        15 RISC-V 64   fstatat 4-arg            -100, 0
        16 PowerPC     stat    2-arg            n/a
        17 MIPS 32     stat64  2-arg            n/a (uses 2-arg ABI)
        18 MIPS 64     stat    2-arg            n/a

    Windows platforms (6, 7) never reach this dispatcher; do_stat short-
    circuits them with -1 before calling.

    AT_FDCWD = -100 is the cross-platform constant on all Linux kernels;
    the flags argument 0 means "follow symlinks like stat", matching POSIX
    stat semantics rather than lstat.

    The 2-arg-vs-4-arg decision is made here at the file_metadata layer
    because the per-platform syscall numbers in get_stat_config encode
    which kernel entrypoint is being called, and only this module knows
    the ABI shape associated with each syscall number.
    :End Note

    Note: 4-arg fstatat platforms: Linux ARM64 (2), RISC-V 32 (14), RISC-V 64 (15)
    If platform_id is equal to 2:
        Return proc syscall_4 from Syscall with syscall_num, minus 100, path, statbuf, 0
    End If
    If platform_id is equal to 14:
        Return proc syscall_4 from Syscall with syscall_num, minus 100, path, statbuf, 0
    End If
    If platform_id is equal to 15:
        Return proc syscall_4 from Syscall with syscall_num, minus 100, path, statbuf, 0
    End If

    Note: 2-arg stat / stat64 / __stat50 on all remaining POSIX platforms
    Return proc syscall_2 from Syscall with syscall_num, path, statbuf
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Public API - File Metadata Operations
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_file_size" that takes file_path as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get file size in bytes

    Let platform_id be proc detect_platform
    Let config be proc get_stat_config with platform_id

    If config is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stat_size be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with config, 8
    Let stat_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with stat_size

    Let result be proc do_stat with file_path, stat_buffer
    If result is not equal to 0:
        Note: stat_buffer is owned-heap; P1-D will add deallocate (deferred)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let st_size_offset be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with config, 16
    Let file_size be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with stat_buffer, st_size_offset

    Note: stat_buffer is owned-heap; P1-D will add deallocate (deferred)
    Return file_size
End Process

Process called "get_file_modification_time" that takes file_path as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get last modification time (seconds since Unix epoch)

    Let platform_id be proc detect_platform
    Let config be proc get_stat_config with platform_id

    If config is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let stat_size be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with config, 8
    Let stat_buffer be proc allocate from Layout with stat_size

    Let result be proc do_stat with file_path, stat_buffer
    If result is not equal to 0:
        Note: stat_buffer is owned-heap; P1-D will add deallocate (deferred)
        Return 0
    End If

    Let st_mtime_offset be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with config, 24
    Let mtime be proc memory_get_qword from MemoryCore with stat_buffer, st_mtime_offset

    Note: stat_buffer is owned-heap; P1-D will add deallocate (deferred)
    Return mtime
End Process

